Well, this topic reminds me of a time when I was doing a group assignment with some friends at university. If I remember correctly, it happened about six months ago, when I was still a second-year student.

There were four of us in the group — two girls and two boys — and I was chosen as the group leader. To keep things fair, I divided the presentation into four parts and let everyone choose the section they felt most confident with. We were given about a week to prepare our parts.

The problem came up during our rehearsal. One of the girls, Ngan, wasn’t satisfied with what Anh had prepared and made a few critical comments about it. However, the way she expressed herself was a bit too direct, so Anh took it personally. From Anh’s point of view, she felt that she had already tried her best and that her work wasn’t as bad as Ngan made it sound.

At first, it was just a small disagreement, but within a few minutes, it turned into quite a heated argument between the two of them. As the group leader, I had to step in and act as a mediator. I tried to calm them down, explained each person’s point of view, and suggested some practical ways for Anh to improve her part. Then we went through the rehearsal together again, but the mood was never the same.

In the end, the presentation went well, but the two of them didn’t really sort things out afterward and even blocked each other on Facebook.

From this experience, I learned that communication skills are incredibly important because if you're not careful with your words, they can easily damage a relationship.
